post_text:
MESD has received approval for K-5 cohort student to return next week. Cohort A will start Tuesday, September 8th and Cohort B will start Thursday, September 10th. Please check your email to find the Superintendent Letter and pages 11-16 COVID-19 Response Toolkit for NM Elementary Schools. There have been some specific guidelines added on symptoms and facemask criteria have been updated. If your child attends face-to-face learning and you have already purchased face-coverings that don‚Äôt meet the new criteria we will provide disposable. The PED will be supplying 2 cloth-mask that meet the criteria but will not be in for several weeks. Face coverings that cannot substitute for face masks are masks that have exhalation valves or vents, bandanas, scarves, neck gaiters or neck fleece, and face shields.
The link to the entire COVID-19 Response Toolkit for NM Elementary Schools will be sent out after a few minor changes from the PED.

post_text:
Dear Moriarty-Edgewood School District Families,

MESD utilizes social media to inform our communities about important information happening throughout the district. It is imperative that the information we communicate is not lost in the divisive chatter and misinformation being communicated (passed, spread, passed on) in the comments section. Therefore, MESD will be removing all future comments to our Facebook page for the social-emotional health of staff and families that follow us and to maintain the delivery of accurate information. If you have specific questions or concerns, I am requesting that you direct them to reentry@mesd.us. This email will go directly to my inbox and our team will try to answer your questions as quickly as possible. As always, student learning is our #1 priority while keeping both students and staff healthy and safe.

Warmest Regards,
Teresa K. Salazar, Superintendent

Criteria for cohorts are currently being developed and will be communicated to families when finalized.

post_text:
MESD is continuing our work on the re-entry plans for the 2020 school year and look to have the specific plan out to families in mid-July. As we finalize different portions of the plan, we will be sending updates to assist families in planning ahead via social media and school messenger between now and then.

In the meantime, we wanted to let you know that MESD is proud to partner with Edgenuity to offer 100% online classes for the 2020 school year! If you are looking for a free educational option for your child to stay at home, or are thinking about homeschool for your child, leave the education to us! To register for distance learning, or for more information, call 505-832-5807.

post_text:
Thank you for participating in our parent survey!
We had over 650 responses and received input on over 1200 students in the district! Your responses indicated that 25% of families will be looking for a complete virtual school experience for students in the fall, while 75% of responses will send students back to physical buildings. We are in the beginning stages of planning for the 2020-2021 school year and will plan according to the DOH and NMPED guidelines, but we are excited to announce that we WILL have options for all families including 100% online instruction in grades K-12.
These options are available to returning and NEW to the district students and families!
Be on the lookout for updates!

Great news! Human Service Department has issued the first phase of benefit of issuance to all student households on May 18th that are currently on SNAP benefits. The benefits went to approximately 87,500 student households in the amount of $313.40 for March, April, and May. The phases of P-EBT benefit issuance will be the following:



Phase 1- Issue Benefits to current SNAP EBT student households (May 18th)

Phase 2- Issue Benefits to current Medicaid student households (By the end of May)

Phase 3 and 4- Issue benefits via mailed P-EBT card to students that receive free and reduced meals that are NOT on SNAP EBT or Medicaid (Early June)

Santa Fe County in partnership with the World Central Kitchen, Santa Fe Community College, Salvation Army, YouthWorks, and Street Food Institute will be distributing meals at no charge to community residents. The meal distribution will begin on Tuesday, May 5, 2020, and continue every Tuesday until further notice.

Edgewood Fire Station
1 Municipal Way, Edgewood
3:00-5:00 p.m.

There are no qualifications for the free meals or questions asked. Santa Fe County continues to work to promote the health and safety of our residents, and if you are in need of food or have questions about the program, please call Lucy Foma, Senior Planner with Santa Fe County‚Äôs Growth Management Department at 505-995-2735 or lfoma@santacountynm.gov.

post_text:
Opportunity for Seniors:

The Class of 2020 is redefining high school graduation with a first-of-its-kind national ceremony. Graduate Together: America Honors the Class of 2020 will air simultaneously across ABC, CBS, FOX, and NBC, as well as a broad alliance of social media and streaming platforms. The one-hour primetime special airs on Saturday, May 16, and will honor the more than 3 million high school seniors across the country.

There are many ways for you to participate! The program is asking for students, teachers and families to share their stories, school spirit and graduation content. Check it out! The content you submit may be included in the TV program, on social media, or in PEOPLE Magazine.

post_text: Attention MHS students and families: Yearbooks will arrive the first or second week of May. No distribution date or times have been set; you will be contacted when that day is decided. More than likely, we will have a drive-up situation when collecting your yearbook. If you have a balance, you will pay at that time. If you have a balance and would like to know what it is or would like to order a yearbook ($60), please contact mhsyearbook@mesd.us. We accept cash or checks, make checks payable to MHS. We will collect money and checks on the day the yearbook is distributed. If you'd like to order online, the link is available on the MESD website.

post_text:
Attention all MESD Families:

Beginning tomorrow, March 26th, teacher teams grade K-8 and high school elective classes will be posting weekly activities on mesd.us in the new learning hub section. Material will be updated by 9:00 am each Thursday morning while schools remain closed. You or your child can simply navigate to the appropriate grade level(s) to access the content. High school core classes will be pushed out by Google Classroom or can be picked up Thursday in the visitor parking lot from 11:00-1:00.
For families who may not have electronic access to this site, we will also distribute printed versions of posted weekly activities during "Grab & Go" lunch distribution times (11:00 am - 1:00 pm) each Thursday and Friday at our campuses. Each of you should have received some kind of contact from your child‚Äôs school on how they would access the learning activities. If you have not heard from someone please call 505.832.4471.

shared_text:
New Mexico Public Education Department
March 24 at 9:33 AM ¬∑

The new Public Health Order issued yesterday does not affect the Public School Closure Period, but an extended closure is likely. We know that you are eagerly awaiting an update and it is our intention to give you as much notice as possible to make plans. As Governor Michelle Lujan Grisham said during the press conference yesterday, "We are working with the federal government-- what waivers need to be in place, what we do about graduations, what we do about college applications, what we do about distance learning and support, how can we assure every student has the same access to that level of learning, which is an important requirement for rural states like this one." We anticipate making an announcement later this week or early next week.
text:
New Mexico Public Education Department
March 24 at 9:33 AM ¬∑

The new Public Health Order issued yesterday does not affect the Public School Closure Period, but an extended closure is likely. We know that you are eagerly awaiting an update and it is our intention to give you as much notice as possible to make plans. As Governor Michelle Lujan Grisham said during the press conference yesterday, "We are working with the federal government-- what waivers need to be in place, what we do about graduations, what we do about college applications, what we do about distance learning and support, how can we assure every student has the same access to that level of learning, which is an important requirement for rural states like this one." We anticipate making an announcement later this week or early next week.

Congratulations to the Moriarty FFA Chapter for winning our December Social Media Challenge!

A tradition cherished by this chapter is their annual Christmas party where members come together to play various minute-to-win-it games and collect toys. The toys are then delivered to the UNMH Carrie Tingly Play Room for their annual Christmas Closet for kids and their siblings who are spending the holiday season in the hospital. This year, the chapter donated almost 80 toys to the hospital!

Congratulations, Moriarty FFA, for your outstanding example of how our holiday traditions can help us #TaketheStep towards a better community!
